1. Niño 3.4 index (10/10)¶

The Nio 3.4 anomalies may be thought of as representing the average equatorial sea surface temperatures (SSTs) across the Pacific from about the dateline to the South American coast (5N-5S, 170W-120W). The Nio 3.4 index typically uses a 3-month running mean, and El Nio or La Nia events are defined when the Nio 3.4 SSTs exceed +/- 0.5C for a period of 5 months or more. Check Equatorial Pacific Sea Surface Temperatures for more about the Nio 3.4 index.

In this problem set, you will use the sea surface temperature (SST) data from NOAA. Download the netCDF4 file (NOAA_NCDC_ERSST_v3b_SST.nc) here.</font>

1.1 [5 points] Compute monthly climatology for SST from Nio 3.4 region, and subtract climatology from SST time series to obtain anomalies.

nino3.4anoma

def smooth(x,width):#3
    out0 = np.convolve(x,np.ones(width,dtype=int),'valid')/width
    r = np.arange(1,width-1,2)  
    start = np.cumsum(x[:width-1])[::2]/r  
    stop = (np.cumsum(x[:-width:-1])[::2]/r)[::-1]  
    return np.concatenate(( start , out0, stop ))
ds_nino_anoma_runnningaver = smooth(ds_nino_anoma,3)#
a = np.maximum(ds_nino_anoma,0)#0
b = np.minimum(ds_nino_anoma,0)#0
X = ds_nino['time']
plt.bar(X,a,width = 150,color = 'r',label='Ei Nino Threshold')
plt.bar(X,b,width = 150,color = 'b',label='La Nina Threshold')
plt.plot(X,ds_nino_anoma_runnningaver,color = 'black',linewidth = 0.8,label='3mth running mean')
plt.axhline(y=0.5, color='r', linestyle='-',alpha=0.2)
plt.axhline(y=-0.5, color='b', linestyle='-',alpha=0.2)
plt.title('SST Anomaly in Nino 3.4 Region (5N-5S,120-170W)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Anomaly in Degress C')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0), loc=3, borderaxespad=0)
plt.show()
